      <div class="content expandableContent">
        <p>
          A three part assignment for the Graphics Animation and Sound class running this semester, Unhappy Flying Reptiles combines elements from Angry Birds and Duck Hunt. Built in C++ and using GDI+ on an MFC foundation, this game serves as an introduction to the intricacies of working with graphics. Frame rates, colour correction, double buffering, and matrix transformations are some of the basic concepts we have been learning to work with in the process of creating this game.
        </p>
        <p>
          Run by the same professor that typically runs the Game Development class in the third year, the Graphics Animation and Sound class gives us an opportunity to explore some of the concepts present in game programming. As such, for this project, we have the opportunity to implement basic physics concepts such as gravity and collision detection as well as the game loop design pattern.
        </p>
        <p>
          To view the source for this project, feel free to take a look at <a href="https://github.com/MeMark2">my GitHub</a> account. The project is available under the MIT license and can be found <a href="https://github.com/MeMark2/UnhappyFlyingReptiles">here</a>.
        </p>
      </div>
